{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WLFsjQN2rQZh5miYUcNU5J","type":"tool_result","content":"90\t\n91\t### AD1: Module Boundaries\n92\t\n93\t| Module | Responsibility | Key FRs |\n94\t|--------|---------------|---------|\n95\t| `workflow-parser` | Parse YAML, validate against JSON schema, resolve patches (embedded→user→project) | FR1-6, FR13-15 |\n96\t| `agent-resolver` | Resolve agent config through patch chain, compile to SDK inline subagent definition | FR7-12 |\n97\t| `workflow-engine` | Execute flow steps, manage iterations, handle `loop:` blocks, inject evaluator findings into retries | FR16-18, FR29-31 |\n98\t| `agent-dispatch` | Call Agent SDK `query()`, manage sessions (fresh/continue), inject trace IDs | FR19-23 |\n99\t| `evaluator` | Blind evaluator workspace setup, spawn, JSON verdict parsing | FR24-28 |\n100\t| `circuit-breaker` | Score-based stagnation detection, score history tracking | FR32-35 |\n101\t| `workflow-state` | Read/write workflow-state.yaml, crash recovery (resume from last completed task) | NFR6-8 |\n102\t\n103\t**Rationale:** 7 modules, each 100-200 LOC. Feedback loop (FR29-30) is part of `workflow-engine` — it's loop logic, not a separate concern. CLI commands (`init`, `run`, `validate`, `status`) are thin wrappers calling these modules. Observability (FR36-37) is a cross-cutting concern handled by trace ID injection in `agent-dispatch`, not a separate module.\n104\t\n105\t### AD2: Evaluator Workspace Isolation\n106\t\n107\t**Decision:** Temp directory with only story files + Docker access.\n108\t\n109\t```\n110\t/tmp/codeharness-verify-{runId}/\n111\t  story-files/     # copied ACs from sprint\n112\t  verdict/         # evaluator writes JSON verdict here\n113\t```\n114\t\n115\tEngine copies story files to temp dir, spawns evaluator with `cwd` set to this directory. Agent SDK options enforce isolation:\n116\t- `bare: true` — no plugins, hooks, MCP, memory\n117\t- `disallowedTools: [\"Edit\", \"Write\"]` — read-only + execute only\n118\t- `cwd: /tmp/codeharness-verify-{runId}` — no source code present\n119\t\n120\t**Rationale:** Simplest approach. Source isn't there because we never put it there. No git worktree complexity, no Docker-in-Docker. The Agent SDK's `cwd` + `disallowedTools` provide sufficient isolation.\n121\t\n122\t### AD3: Embedded Template Storage\n123\t\n124\t**Decision:** `templates/` directory in the npm package.\n125\t\n126\t```\n127\ttemplates/\n128\t  agents/\n129\t    dev.yaml\n130\t    qa.yaml\n131\t    architect.yaml\n132\t    pm.yaml\n133\t    sm.yaml\n134\t    analyst.yaml\n135\t    ux-designer.yaml\n136\t    tech-writer.yaml\n137\t    evaluator.yaml\n138\t  workflows/\n139\t    default.yaml\n140\t```\n141\t\n142\tIncluded via `package.json` `files` array. Readable, editable for debugging, consistent with existing pattern (`templates/Dockerfile.verify`).\n143\t\n144\t**Rationale:** Files over compiled strings. Easier to inspect, diff, and debug. The `codeharness init` command copies the default workflow to the project; embedded agents are resolved at runtime from the package location.\n145\t\n146\t### AD4: Config Resolution Caching\n147\t\n148\t**Decision:** Resolve all configs once at engine startup, cache in memory.\n149\t\n150\tOn `codeharness run`:\n151\t1. Resolve workflow: load embedded → apply user patch → apply project patch → cache\n152\t2. Resolve all referenced agents: same resolution chain → cache\n153\t3. Run engine with cached configs — no file I/O during execution\n154\t\n155\t**Rationale:** Config files don't change during a run. Caching guarantees NFR2 (<200ms resolution) and eliminates repeated file system reads during long-running execution.\n156\t\n157\t### AD5: Evaluator Verdict Schema\n158\t\n159\t**Decision:** Structured JSON enforced by Agent SDK `jsonSchema` option.\n160\t\n161\t```typescript\n162\tinterface EvaluatorVerdict {\n163\t  verdict: 'pass' | 'fail';\n164\t  score: {\n165\t    passed: number;\n166\t    failed: number;\n167\t    unknown: number;\n168\t    total: number;\n169\t  };\n170\t  findings: Array<{\n171\t    ac: number;\n172\t    description: string;\n173\t    status: 'pass' | 'fail' | 'unknown';\n174\t    evidence: {\n175\t      commands_run: string[];\n176\t      output_observed: string;\n177\t      reasoning: string;\n178\t    };\n179\t  }>;\n180\t  evaluator_trace_id: string;\n181\t  duration_seconds: number;\n182\t}\n183\t```\n184\t\n185\t**Rationale:** Replaces the 175-line proof document regex parser entirely. The Agent SDK validates the output against this schema — if the evaluator doesn't produce valid JSON, the SDK rejects it. Every AC verdict requires evidence (commands + output), enforcing the anti-leniency principle structurally.\n186\t\n187\t### Decision Impact Analysis\n188\t\n189\t**Implementation Sequence:**\n190\t1. `workflow-state` — foundation for crash recovery, needed by everything\n191\t2. `workflow-parser` — parse YAML + resolve patches, needed before execution\n192\t3. `agent-resolver` — resolve agent configs, needed before dispatch\n193\t4. `agent-dispatch` — SDK integration, needed before engine can run\n194\t5. `workflow-engine` — orchestrates everything above\n195\t6. `evaluator` — depends on dispatch + state\n196\t7. `circuit-breaker` — depends on evaluator verdicts\n197\t\n198\t**Cross-Component Dependencies:**\n199\t- `workflow-engine` depends on all other modules\n200\t- `evaluator` depends on `agent-dispatch` (for SDK spawn) and `workflow-state` (for verdict recording)\n201\t- `circuit-breaker` depends on `workflow-state` (reads score history)\n202\t- `agent-dispatch` depends on `agent-resolver` (for compiled subagent definitions)\n203\t\n204\t## Implementation Patterns & Consistency Rules\n205\t\n206\t### Naming Patterns\n207\t\n208\t**File naming:** `kebab-case.ts` for all source files. Already established (`workflow-parser.ts`, `agent-dispatch.ts`).\n209\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XjpGmYRgdBb6aeHBV1bdT9","session_id":"e9c90575-92e6-47e7-805a-c4ec47a0ac4f","uuid":"3fbf8046-ec2b-4af0-9056-30a2fdd8bd03","timestamp":"2026-04-02T23:38:44.550Z"}
